[{"id":"VH965729","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH965666.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">After the processes, in which direction, if any, is the net electric force exerted on sphere 2Â ?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH965729_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of three identical conducting spheres on insulating stands that are spaced at equal distances apart, labeled Sphere 1, Sphere 2, and Sphere 3. Sphere 1 is shown with a charge of Q sub 0. A note indicates that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" height=\"149\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH965666.g01.png\" width=\"210\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Three identical conducting spheres are arranged on insulating stands and equally spaced, as shown. Sphere 1 initially has a net charge of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 0\"><math alttext=\"Q sub 0\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> , while spheres 2 and 3 are initially uncharged. Sphere 1 is touched briefly to sphere 2 and moved away; then sphere 2 is touched briefly to sphere 3 and moved away.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">In no direction, because the net force is zero</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">To the left</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">To the right</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It cannot be determined without knowing the charge distribution on the surface of the spheres.</p>"],"answer":2}]